{"key":"post-12698655","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12698655</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;insipidtoast said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I know standard procedure for sterilizing is to bring PC up to 15 psi, let stay at high for 5 min, then switch the stove down to low.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Put the stove on high with no weight on the nozzle.&amp;nbsp; It should be open to vent for five to ten minutes worth of steam escaping.&amp;nbsp; After that, put the weight on and once 15 psi is reached it will begin to jiggle.&amp;nbsp; At this point, turn down the burner to the point where it rattles no more than a few times per minute.&amp;nbsp; If it rattles more than that, you're losing water from the PC, but also from the moisture within your jars.&amp;nbsp; I use a gauge and turn the stove to the lowest setting that will maintain 14 psi, therefore NO rattling of the weight.&amp;nbsp;  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Since you don't have a gauge, you'll have to let the weight rattle a few times per minute, but more than that risks it running dry, or drying out your substrates.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12698337</prev>\n<first>12698337</first>\n<last>12698655</last>\n<when>1275869369</when>\n<utime>06/07/10 03:09 AM</utime>\n</post>"}